{{About|a city in [[Kharkiv Oblast]]|other populated places, particularly in [[Poland]]|Lubotyn (disambiguation)|other populated localities with the Russian-like transliteration|Lubotin (disambiguation)}} {{Infobox settlement |official_name = Liubotyn |native_name = Люботин |other_name = |image_skyline = St. Nicholas Church, Lyubotyn.jpg |imagesize = |image_caption = St. Nicholas Church in Liubotyn |image_flag = Lubotyn prapor.png |image_shield = Lubotyn gerb.png |shield_size = |subdivision_type = Country |subdivision_name = {{UKR}} |subdivision_type1 = [[Oblast]] |subdivision_name1 = [[Kharkiv Oblast]] |subdivision_type2 = [[Municipality]] |subdivision_name2 = [[Liubotyn Municipality]] |leader_title = Mayor |leader_name = |established_title = Founded |established_date =1650 |area_total_km2 =31,1 |population_as_of = 2017 |population_total = 21328 |population_density_km2 = |timezone = EET |utc_offset = +2 |timezone_DST = EEST |utc_offset_DST = +3 |postal_code_type = Postal code |postal_code =62433-62436 |website =[https://web.archive.org/web/20110511153506/http://lubotin.com/ Archived] |footnotes = }} '''Liubotyn''' ({{lang-uk|Люботин}}, {{lang-ru|Люботин}}, [[Romanization of Russian|translit.]] ''Lyubotyn'') is a city in [[Kharkiv Oblast]] ([[oblast|province]]) of eastern [[Ukraine]]. It is designated as a separate [[raion]] (district), as a [[city of regional significance (Ukraine)|city of oblast significance]]. Population: {{Ua-pop-est2017|21,328}}
==History== The city was established in 1650 by Ukrainian Cossacks from the [[right-bank Ukraine]].
During [[World War II]], Liubotyn was under [[Nazi Germany|German]] occupation from 20 October 1941 to 22 February 1943 and again from 9 March to 29 August 1943.
